    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-04-21T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-04-21T00:00:00-05:00" n="834"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d834">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">325.1121 Bethune, Larry K./46</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Chile</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Santiago</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-04-21">April 21,
                            1931</date>.<lb/>[Received May 2.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 845</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to refer to this Embassy’s
                    despatch No. 819 of March 27, 1931,<note n="25" xml:id="d834fn25">Not
                        printed.</note> with special reference to enclosure No. 6, and to report
                    that the Chilean Supreme Court, on April 21st, and by a vote of four to one,
                    denied the appeal of Brusadelli y Manni from the decision of the Court of
                    Appeals. By the latter decision, made on March 21, 1931, the Court of Appeals
                    acted favorably on the appeal (similar to habeas corpus) presented by the
                    attorneys for General Motors on behalf of Mr. Bethune, who was released and
                    whose bond was cancelled.</p>
                <p>This decision of the Supreme Court confirms the justice of the Embassy’s protest
                    against the illegality of the arrest of Mr. Bethune and of his being held <hi
                        rend="italic">incomunicado.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">R. Henry Norweb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
